WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.840
Hey. Hi. Welcome, everybody. I'd like to start our session on

2
00:00:04.380 --> 00:00:08.300
advancing precision approaches to head and neck cancer. I'm Barbara Bertness.

3
00:00:08.380 --> 00:00:11.760
I'm a medical oncologist at Yale School of Medicine.

4
00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:17.380
So just as a brief introduction to head and neck squamous cell carcinoma, this is

5
00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:21.160
a relatively common cancer, the seventh most common cancer

6
00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:25.140
globally. We estimate about 890,000 new

7
00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:28.740
cases a year, so it's just under 5% of new cancer

8
00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:32.589
diagnoses and almost half a million deaths every

9
00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:36.380
year. So again, just under 5% of global cancer deaths.

10
00:00:36.420 --> 00:00:40.400
The risk factors for head and neck cancer are age, nutritional status,

11
00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:44.220
alcohol exposure, exposure to tobacco and other oral

12
00:00:44.300 --> 00:00:47.960
carcinogens, and I think an open question there is whether or not

13
00:00:48.020 --> 00:00:51.449
vape is going to turn out to be a driver of head and neck cancer,

14
00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:55.380
germline DNA repair abnormalities, and human

15
00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:57.100
papillomavirus.

16
00:00:59.340 --> 00:01:02.670
An interesting thing about a cancer with these diverse

17
00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:04.860
causes is that,

18
00:01:05.920 --> 00:01:09.460
across these diverse etiologies, there are actually

19
00:01:09.520 --> 00:01:12.440
commonalities in what signaling pathways are disrupted.

20
00:01:12.940 --> 00:01:16.820
So we see loss of p53 function, whether it arises through

21
00:01:16.840 --> 00:01:20.740
mutation, as is common in HPV-independent head and neck

22
00:01:20.780 --> 00:01:24.320
cancer, or because a viral oncoprotein is leading to

23
00:01:24.340 --> 00:01:27.620
degradation of p53, as is the case in

24
00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:31.350
HPV-associated cancers, CDKN2A mutation and

25
00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:34.280
amplification, PIK3CA mutation or amplification.

26
00:01:35.020 --> 00:01:38.200
Then there's this observation that patients who are adult

27
00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:41.360
survivors of Fanconi anemia, whether or not they've been

28
00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:45.630
transplanted, have an extraordinarily high rate of head and

29
00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:46.340
neck cancers.

30
00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:51.220
And a parallel observation that something like a quarter of sporadic

31
00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:55.400
HPV-negative head and neck cancer also displays mutation within that

32
00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:59.060
pathway. And so one of the things I think

33
00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:03.160
people in the field are doing is asking whether or not these

34
00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:06.880
insights point to shared therapeutic vulnerabilities across the different

35
00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:08.241
types of head and neck cancer.

36
00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:12.660
We do naturally categorize these cancers as

37
00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:16.790
HPV-related or HPV independent, and you'll

38
00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:17.600
see that that's

39
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.380
somewhat the approach we've taken to this session as well.

40
00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:25.540
And the reason for this is not only the different etiologic

41
00:02:25.620 --> 00:02:28.880
basis, but also a different natural history.

42
00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:33.019
So HPV-associated cancer tends to be somewhat less

43
00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:36.520
aggressive and is much more treatment responsive.

44
00:02:36.570 --> 00:02:40.420
And these data here come from a national study of chemoradiation

45
00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:44.500
where the overall survival for patients with oropharynx cancer that was

46
00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:48.360
HPV-related as opposed to HPV unrelated, was very

47
00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.340
dramatically different, as you can see here.

48
00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:56.500
We focus a lot on treatment resistance, partly because the majority

49
00:02:56.560 --> 00:03:00.500
of patients with head and neck cancer present with a locally advanced

50
00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:04.560
cancer. And so they present with a stage of

51
00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:08.260
disease that we attempt to cure, whether that's with surgery, radiation,

52
00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:11.740
chemoradiation, or some mix of those, with or without

53
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.800
immunotherapy. And for HPV-related cancers, about 80% are

54
00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:19.300
cured. For HPV unrelated, about 50% are cured.

55
00:03:19.660 --> 00:03:23.240
And as you'll be hearing from the next speaker, some HPV-related cancers

56
00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:27.140
probably can be cured with much less intensive therapy than we currently give.

57
00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:31.820
We've known for a long time that combination chemotherapy is active but not

58
00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:35.080
curative. Immunotherapy now provides a long-term

59
00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:39.140
survival benefit for a proportion of patients who

60
00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:42.810
have recurrent metastatic disease and a proportion of patients who are

61
00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:46.340
resectable, but many patients don't derive substantial benefit

62
00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:48.940
from immunotherapy as we're currently giving it.

63
00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:53.540
And if we look at the genomic signature of these cancers, loss of

64
00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:57.080
tumor suppressor function is the predominant event in

65
00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:00.840
HPV-negative cancer, and this has slowed advances in targeted

66
00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:01.240
treatment.

67
00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:07.240
To sum up what I see as sort of our clinical and translational research

68
00:04:07.340 --> 00:04:11.020
goals in head and neck cancer, firstly, I think to appropriately define risk and

69
00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:14.600
treatment sensitivity so we can tailor the treatments that we've already

70
00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:18.280
shown lead to survival advantages in terms of intensity and

71
00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:21.950
duration. To extend the utility of immunotherapy with

72
00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:26.060
rational combinations, and those might or might not be rational combinations

73
00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:27.580
with other immunotherapy agents.

74
00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:32.000
To add targeted treatment that's appropriate to the molecular profile of the

75
00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:34.550
subset of head and neck cancer that you're dealing with.

76
00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:38.810
I think that's likely to differ by HPV status, as I'll show you a little bit.

77
00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:42.360
And then if we are successful in incorporating more targeted

78
00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:45.860
therapies, address the adaptive resistance that we know will emerge.

79
00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:49.730
So this is the agenda we've put together to try to address this.

80
00:04:49.860 --> 00:04:51.130
First, I'll be asking,

81
00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:55.560
how can we make better progress with precision approaches to

82
00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:57.050
HPV-independent cancer?

83
00:04:57.900 --> 00:05:01.040
Then, Del Yarbrough, a surgeon scientist who's chair of

84
00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:04.560
otolaryngology at Chapel Hill, will talk about subtypes of

85
00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:07.110
HPV-initiated head and neck cancer.

86
00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:10.110
What are the implications for de-escalation and precision therapy?

87
00:05:10.580 --> 00:05:14.120
And then Dr. Ari Rosenberg, who's an associate medical

88
00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:18.040
oncologist, associate professor at the University of Chicago, will address

89
00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:22.050
minimal residual disease and treatment optimization in head and neck cancer.

90
00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:25.740
So I'll dive right into my talk, Precision Approaches to

91
00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:29.580
HPV-Independent Head and Neck Cancer. Here are my disclosures.

92
00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:35.760
And so we do know a lot about the molecular profile of these

93
00:05:35.800 --> 00:05:39.500
cancers. But what I've done with the color coding here is try to indicate

94
00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:42.600
how little of that we actually use in treatment decision-making.

95
00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:46.220
So we can make treatment decisions based on PD-L1 and tumor

96
00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:50.200
mutation burden. We have a sort of global approach to

97
00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:53.910
HPV-negative head and neck cancer that derives from the observation about

98
00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:56.820
overexpression of epidermal growth factor receptor.

99
00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:00.960
And then we don't do very much, with other things that we know to be very

100
00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:04.500
important, such as p53 mutations, CDKN2A

101
00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:08.220
mutation or amplification, hypoxia, and an immune

102
00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:11.910
microenvironment that's rich in cancer-associated fibroblasts and

103
00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:15.900
myeloid-derived cells.So let's start with PD-L1

104
00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:19.740
expression. This is from the KEYNOTE-048 trial, which was a study

105
00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:23.600
that looked at incorporating pembrolizumab into treatment of patients in the

106
00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:25.980
first line for recurrent metastatic head neck cancer,

107
00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:30.520
and compared either pembrolizumab monotherapy or pembrolizumab

108
00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:34.100
plus chemo to an older standard of chemotherapy plus the

109
00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:36.540
EGFR-targeted antibody cetuximab.

110
00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:38.520
And as you can see here,

111
00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:43.140
the hazard ratio as you move from the total population to the population

112
00:06:43.180 --> 00:06:46.060
of cancers with PD-L1 expression to those with

113
00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:49.620
PD-L1-rich expression, the hazard ratio improves from

114
00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:53.380
0.72 to 0.63 for pembrolizumab plus

115
00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:56.780
chemotherapy, and the five-year survival crosses the

116
00:06:56.920 --> 00:07:00.200
20% mark for the first time in this disease.

117
00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:04.200
We went back and looked about what about the PD-L1 low patients, and

118
00:07:04.260 --> 00:07:08.150
so here for pembrolizumab alone and here for pembrolizumab plus chemotherapy,

119
00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:12.560
you can see there is an advantage to the use of pembrolizumab in those with CPS

120
00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:16.360
1 to 19. But for those who express really essentially no

121
00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:20.510
PD-L1, it's deleterious to use pembrolizumab alone,

122
00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:23.360
and it's no better to use pembrolizumab plus chemo.

123
00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:28.340
So I think we're all using PD-L1 expression in daily practice in head neck

124
00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:30.940
cancer. What about tumor mutation burden?

125
00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:34.240
Because we link that to sensitivity to immunotherapy.

126
00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:38.480
So, if you look at the top panel here, this is from the

127
00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:42.950
TCGA, and if you focus in the second bar here, the gray

128
00:07:43.040 --> 00:07:45.050
ones are the ones that are HPV negative.

129
00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:49.270
Whether those patients are smokers or non-smokers, whatever the anatomic

130
00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:53.060
site of the head neck cancer is, you can see across the board, they tend to have an

131
00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:55.600
elevation in non-synonymous mutations.

132
00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:59.380
And Robert Haddad used this information to look at

133
00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:03.420
response to pembrolizumab in an early trial in treatment refractory

134
00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:07.280
disease, and you can see for both HPV negative and HPV positive,

135
00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:11.600
there's at least a numeric improvement in response rate for those patients with a

136
00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:13.560
higher non-synonymous mutation burden.

137
00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:18.860
And there is, in fact, FDA approval for using PD-1 inhibition

138
00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:22.860
in TMB high cancers. So those two things, I think, are firmly

139
00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:24.140
established in practice.

140
00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:29.500
We looked to see whether or not there could be a tie-in to p53,

141
00:08:29.660 --> 00:08:32.900
so I did this work with Erika Golemis and the people at Caris

142
00:08:32.961 --> 00:08:36.240
Biosciences, looking at 1,000 HPV negative head neck

143
00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:38.000
cancers. And

144
00:08:39.680 --> 00:08:43.660
we looked at the p53 mutations by whether they were disruptive, by

145
00:08:43.701 --> 00:08:47.660
whether or not they led to a loss of function or a gain of function, whether or

146
00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:51.140
not they impacted truncation or the DNA binding domain.

147
00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:54.930
And sort of across the board, you can see that either p53 mutation,

148
00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:58.520
as long as it wasn't a gain-of-function mutation, or

149
00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:02.029
CDKN2A abnormalities led to a higher

150
00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:06.100
TMB. Co-occurrence of the two mutations

151
00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:10.100
led to an even higher TMB, and then we used TMB of 15

152
00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:13.640
or higher sort of as a cut point for might be good

153
00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:17.580
candidates for immunotherapy. And here, across the board, whether you look at the

154
00:09:17.600 --> 00:09:21.560
blue lines, which are p53, the green, which are CDKN2A,

155
00:09:21.620 --> 00:09:25.600
or the red, which are co-mutation, you can see that the mutations did

156
00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:29.500
drive a higher incidence of high TMB, with the exception of

157
00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:31.820
the gain-of-function p53 mutations.

158
00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:36.860
Well, what about EGFR? This has been recognized since the

159
00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:40.380
1990s when Jenny Grandis reported overexpression of

160
00:09:40.420 --> 00:09:44.340
EGFR and TGF-alpha in head neck cancer relative to adjacent

161
00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:45.080
normal tissue.

162
00:09:46.120 --> 00:09:49.749
This is protein overexpression, ligand overexpression, and

163
00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:53.620
protein amplification. Mutation of the receptor is

164
00:09:53.660 --> 00:09:57.060
not common in head neck cancer, in contrast to some forms of lung cancer.

165
00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:01.180
And this has led to molecular therapy with cetuximab since the early

166
00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:01.920
2000s.

167
00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:06.780
We understand from correlative studies and some of the

168
00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:10.650
randomized trials, either with cetuximab or with EGFR-directed

169
00:10:10.680 --> 00:10:13.930
TKIs, that resistance can arise from

170
00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:17.460
abnormalities in downstream signaling, very analogous to colon

171
00:10:17.500 --> 00:10:21.080
cancer, with the one difference that this has never made it into clinical practice

172
00:10:21.100 --> 00:10:23.040
in head neck cancer, which is somewhat regrettable.

173
00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:27.700
But loss of PTEN, mutation in PIK3CA, mutation in RAS are

174
00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:31.240
associated with resistance. And then we see, either at

175
00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:35.080
baseline or in the adaptive response to EGFR inhibition,

176
00:10:35.540 --> 00:10:38.920
upregulation of HER3, MET, and AXL, and

177
00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:42.540
co-expression of these receptors is associated with

178
00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:44.060
cetuximab resistance.

179
00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:48.720
We know that inhibition of EGFR and HER

180
00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:52.520
family members more generally fosters a partial EMT or

181
00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:56.440
indeed a full out epithelial to mesenchymal transition, and this is

182
00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:58.620
associated with treatment resistance.

183
00:10:59.160 --> 00:10:59.500
And

184
00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:04.100
Amanda Psiri and David Rim have shown that EGFR can be

185
00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:07.380
translocated to the nucleus where it sort of hides from

186
00:11:07.420 --> 00:11:08.120
cetuximab.

187
00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:09.380
So,

188
00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:13.660
one of the things that's been sort of interesting is that

189
00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:18.020
there've been a lot of clinical trials with the pan-HER

190
00:11:18.060 --> 00:11:22.000
inhibitor afatinib, which have really failed to show much of an

191
00:11:22.060 --> 00:11:25.780
advance over cetuximab alone. Here, Jungwoo Lee in the

192
00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:29.040
lab developed some afatinib- and erlotinib-resistant

193
00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:33.740
cell line models, and working with Flavio Silva at Fox

194
00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:37.780
Chase, we looked at induction of EMT in these

195
00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:41.900
models. So first of all, it appeared as if

196
00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:46.460
the pan-HER inhibition more strongly drove

197
00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:47.660
EMT than

198
00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:52.360
erlotinib alone, and I'll come back to that for some therapeutic implications at

199
00:11:52.420 --> 00:11:56.076
the end of the talk.Well, I mentioned that cetuximab

200
00:11:56.896 --> 00:12:00.136
cannot access EGFR when it's located in the nucleus.

201
00:12:00.676 --> 00:12:04.516
Nuclear EGFR is known to have some non-canonical effects in stabilizing

202
00:12:04.616 --> 00:12:08.536
PCNA. So we undertook a trial where we looked at adding

203
00:12:08.576 --> 00:12:11.776
a TKI, which would be able to access the receptor

204
00:12:11.816 --> 00:12:15.156
intracellularly to the combination of chemotherapy and

205
00:12:15.236 --> 00:12:19.096
cetuximab, and this was reported by Aarti Batia last

206
00:12:19.176 --> 00:12:22.956
year. So when we gave chemotherapy and cetuximab together in cycle one,

207
00:12:23.036 --> 00:12:26.796
that led to an objective response rate of 33%, spot on for what

208
00:12:26.816 --> 00:12:29.136
the randomized phase three trial had shown.

209
00:12:29.556 --> 00:12:33.456
When we added erlotinib in cycle two, this increased the response rate

210
00:12:33.466 --> 00:12:35.156
to 62.5%.

211
00:12:36.016 --> 00:12:39.506
And I'd like to talk you through some of the post-treatment biopsies that we got on

212
00:12:39.516 --> 00:12:40.985
this study. So first of all, this

213
00:12:42.196 --> 00:12:43.956
case that I picked out of a responder,

214
00:12:44.916 --> 00:12:48.356
I want to start out by highlighting had no P10 expression, which ordinarily is

215
00:12:48.416 --> 00:12:51.156
associated with resistance to cetuximab.

216
00:12:51.496 --> 00:12:53.736
And then down here we have the EGFR expression.

217
00:12:54.176 --> 00:12:58.096
After one cycle of treatment with cetuximab, there's downregulation

218
00:12:58.116 --> 00:13:01.936
of the amount of EGFR expressed, but there's persistence of intracellular

219
00:13:02.096 --> 00:13:05.296
and nuclear EGFR in a subset of the cells.

220
00:13:05.736 --> 00:13:09.056
And then when we added erlotinib, that's completely abrogated.

221
00:13:09.536 --> 00:13:13.366
So I think highlighting and as I talk about some of the bispecifics in a second,

222
00:13:14.236 --> 00:13:17.966
the idea that you can enhance degradation of EGFR might be very

223
00:13:17.976 --> 00:13:20.836
important to addressing nuclear EGFR function.

224
00:13:22.076 --> 00:13:25.656
So after several decades of the only EGFR inhibitor that's been

225
00:13:25.696 --> 00:13:29.136
available to us in head-neck cancer has been cetuximab,

226
00:13:29.656 --> 00:13:32.936
now there are some clinical trials moving forward with bispecifics

227
00:13:33.316 --> 00:13:36.776
that critically address EMT and

228
00:13:38.276 --> 00:13:42.126
early induction of resistance. And so I'd like to talk through some of those.

229
00:13:42.486 --> 00:13:46.456
I'm sorry that because of time, I can't also address antibody combinations

230
00:13:46.496 --> 00:13:47.876
and antibody drug conjugates.

231
00:13:49.616 --> 00:13:52.316
So the first I'd like to talk about is ficaserafusp.

232
00:13:52.636 --> 00:13:56.576
This is a bispecific that targets EGFR and TGF-beta.

233
00:13:57.276 --> 00:14:01.026
And although as a monotherapy, it had a very low response rate,

234
00:14:01.236 --> 00:14:04.796
one out of 42 patients, we've seen very exciting data in

235
00:14:04.936 --> 00:14:06.396
combination with pembrolizumab.

236
00:14:06.476 --> 00:14:10.256
So here you see ficaserafusp plus

237
00:14:10.336 --> 00:14:14.306
pembrolizumab in HPV negative PD-L1 expressing cancers with

238
00:14:14.316 --> 00:14:17.765
a response rate of 54%. And even more remarkably, I

239
00:14:17.836 --> 00:14:21.596
think a median overall survival for this HPV negative population

240
00:14:21.636 --> 00:14:22.516
over 20 months.

241
00:14:23.816 --> 00:14:27.116
Dan Zandberg presented at the multidisciplinary meeting in February

242
00:14:27.716 --> 00:14:31.616
