00:29:37.512 --> 00:29:39.552
a G1S block. So,

501
00:29:40.872 --> 00:29:41.852
also that.

502
00:29:42.232 --> 00:29:42.592
Yes.

503
00:29:42.832 --> 00:29:43.072
Thank you.

504
00:29:44.692 --> 00:29:48.141
Those are great questions. CDK9 has not really come out of our

505
00:29:49.772 --> 00:29:53.352
RNA-seq or proteomics as a big hit, but we haven't

506
00:29:53.652 --> 00:29:57.512
specifically interrogated it. In terms of RB,

507
00:29:58.652 --> 00:30:01.992
I will say that we have more trouble

508
00:30:02.132 --> 00:30:05.502
seeing activity of this combination in HPV-associated

509
00:30:05.592 --> 00:30:07.982
cancers where RB is

510
00:30:07.992 --> 00:30:11.434
degraded.Although

511
00:30:11.434 --> 00:30:15.284
aurora does play a really interesting role in adaptive resistance to

512
00:30:15.324 --> 00:30:17.344
pan-HER inhibition in that setting.

513
00:30:17.504 --> 00:30:18.184
So,

514
00:30:19.104 --> 00:30:21.884
I do think that Rb is also a really important

515
00:30:22.884 --> 00:30:23.304
question.

516
00:30:24.704 --> 00:30:25.044
Okay.

517
00:30:26.324 --> 00:30:29.464
Thank you all very much. So now I'm really pleased to introduce

518
00:30:30.624 --> 00:30:33.224
Dale Yarbrough, who's going to talk about

519
00:30:34.084 --> 00:30:35.344
HPV-associated cancer.

520
00:30:38.664 --> 00:30:41.244
Use this to advance and use that as your mouse.

521
00:30:41.424 --> 00:30:41.784
Roger.

522
00:30:43.364 --> 00:30:43.844
All right. Well,

523
00:30:45.364 --> 00:30:48.384
thanks, Barbara. I'd like to thank you for inviting me, and

524
00:30:49.504 --> 00:30:53.474
the organizers. We're going to talk about something that's a little bit

525
00:30:53.504 --> 00:30:56.544
different, talk about HPV-associated cancers.

526
00:30:56.624 --> 00:31:00.184
I'm Dale Yarbrough from UNC, and I'd like to tell you

527
00:31:00.224 --> 00:31:03.884
today about some studies that have progressed in our

528
00:31:03.944 --> 00:31:07.104
lab over the last several years that identify a

529
00:31:07.124 --> 00:31:09.664
biomarker and a new treatment for

530
00:31:09.844 --> 00:31:11.984
HPV-associated cancer,

531
00:31:12.844 --> 00:31:15.683
and moving towards precision medicine.

532
00:31:17.464 --> 00:31:19.404
So just a little bit of history with HPV.

533
00:31:19.444 --> 00:31:23.064
It hasn't been all that long ago, in the mid-'70s, Harald zur

534
00:31:23.124 --> 00:31:23.524
Hausen

535
00:31:25.104 --> 00:31:28.824
associated causality of HPV with uterine

536
00:31:28.864 --> 00:31:32.504
cervical cancer, and 30 years later got the Nobel Prize for it.

537
00:31:32.764 --> 00:31:35.964
But you can see some of the key players here that uncovered

538
00:31:36.044 --> 00:31:39.984
carcinogenesis. Karl Munger and Denise Galloway really did

539
00:31:40.024 --> 00:31:43.744
seminal work on E6 and E7 functions to inhibit

540
00:31:43.784 --> 00:31:47.024
p53 and Rb. You can see the genomics and

541
00:31:47.064 --> 00:31:48.074
epidemiology

542
00:31:50.304 --> 00:31:53.904
contributions here. But I'd like to really point out the vaccine that was

543
00:31:53.944 --> 00:31:57.864
enabled by the development of virus-like particles from Doug Lowy

544
00:31:57.944 --> 00:31:59.204
and John Schiller.

545
00:32:00.304 --> 00:32:04.144
Now, head and neck cancer association with HPV came much

546
00:32:04.244 --> 00:32:06.064
later than this, although

547
00:32:06.964 --> 00:32:07.784
Frans van Abb ringen

548
00:32:09.564 --> 00:32:10.134
described

549
00:32:11.144 --> 00:32:13.784
HPV in head and neck cancers very early on.

550
00:32:14.444 --> 00:32:16.634
But Margillison's group really,

551
00:32:17.704 --> 00:32:21.524
along with others, popularized the causality in head and neck

552
00:32:21.584 --> 00:32:24.924
cancer. And Lewis and Westra

553
00:32:25.744 --> 00:32:28.284
worked to establish p16 as a surrogate marker

554
00:32:29.484 --> 00:32:32.914
of the disease. Sturgis and Chadhavedi described

555
00:32:32.984 --> 00:32:36.814
epidemiology, along with the Hopkins group, where this

556
00:32:36.824 --> 00:32:39.644
disease has continued to increase over the years.

557
00:32:40.624 --> 00:32:44.084
Many leaders in the fields have addressed deescalation with

558
00:32:44.224 --> 00:32:44.764
surgery,

559
00:32:45.564 --> 00:32:48.564
induction therapy, cetuximab, and

560
00:32:49.684 --> 00:32:52.504
commonly using smoking and tumor stage,

561
00:32:53.264 --> 00:32:57.244
including Bob Ferris and Biswam Chara, Sue

562
00:32:57.284 --> 00:32:58.264
Yam, and

563
00:32:59.124 --> 00:33:00.594
our own Barbara Burtness.

564
00:33:02.984 --> 00:33:06.874
One thing that wasn't really addressed by this was

565
00:33:06.884 --> 00:33:09.524
carcinogenesis, and that's totally understandable.

566
00:33:11.404 --> 00:33:15.204
No one would have any idea that just affecting a different area of the

567
00:33:16.244 --> 00:33:19.904
body would change how HPV creates

568
00:33:19.964 --> 00:33:20.524
cancer

569
00:33:21.664 --> 00:33:25.624
or infects the cells. But our group really

570
00:33:27.944 --> 00:33:31.904
had a clue to this when we started working on subtypes,

571
00:33:32.064 --> 00:33:35.684
and one of the first clues for the

572
00:33:35.724 --> 00:33:39.524
subtype was discovery of mutations of two NF-kappa B

573
00:33:39.584 --> 00:33:43.524
regulators that came out of the TCGA, TRAF3 and CYLD.

574
00:33:44.604 --> 00:33:44.744
And

575
00:33:45.564 --> 00:33:49.104
these mutations were rare in HPV negative tumors,

576
00:33:49.784 --> 00:33:53.524
and their absence in uterine cervical cancer was really an early

577
00:33:53.644 --> 00:33:57.604
signal that there may be a different HPV carcinogenesis pathway in

578
00:33:57.724 --> 00:33:58.143
action.

579
00:34:00.104 --> 00:34:03.624
We also noted that tumors harboring these mutations

580
00:34:04.084 --> 00:34:07.444
in TRAF or CYLD had improved survival.

581
00:34:10.144 --> 00:34:13.864
We went on to confirm these results using unsupervised gene

582
00:34:13.924 --> 00:34:15.245
expression analysis,

583
00:34:16.624 --> 00:34:17.504
which found that

584
00:34:18.424 --> 00:34:21.644
one expression cluster, the sky blue in the pie chart,

585
00:34:23.745 --> 00:34:27.705
naturally segregated tumors into subtypes based on high or

586
00:34:27.765 --> 00:34:30.824
low expression, as shown in the histogram below.

587
00:34:31.924 --> 00:34:35.624
Remarkably, gene set enrichment analysis revealed that NF-kappa B

588
00:34:35.725 --> 00:34:39.504
activation was the defining characteristic of the expressed

589
00:34:39.564 --> 00:34:40.765
genes in this cluster.

590
00:34:41.644 --> 00:34:45.604
And all deactivating mutations of TRAF3 or CYLD were

591
00:34:45.665 --> 00:34:48.824
found in the low-risk subtype identified by these

592
00:34:48.844 --> 00:34:52.745
clusters, confirming that this analysis

593
00:34:52.784 --> 00:34:56.344
basically identified the same subtypes that were identified by

594
00:34:56.444 --> 00:34:57.764
mutation analysis.

595
00:35:00.844 --> 00:35:04.244
Using this expression set, a high-risk and low-risk

596
00:35:04.304 --> 00:35:07.364
subtype of HPV-associated carcinoma

597
00:35:08.244 --> 00:35:12.184
were defined with tumors in the high-risk subtype in the gold

598
00:35:12.204 --> 00:35:14.304
and red, and in the low risk,

599
00:35:15.284 --> 00:35:18.384
having worse survival than the low-risk subtypes, which are in the blue and

600
00:35:18.464 --> 00:35:22.024
black. As you can see, smoking did not decrease

601
00:35:22.104 --> 00:35:25.944
survival in the low-risk subtype, as shown by the overlap of the blue and black

602
00:35:26.484 --> 00:35:28.524
lines in the low-risk subtype.

603
00:35:30.484 --> 00:35:33.584
So this is a schematic of HPV

604
00:35:33.624 --> 00:35:36.684
carcinogenesis that was described in uterine cervical cancer.

605
00:35:37.324 --> 00:35:41.044
And one key part of that is viral integration

606
00:35:41.684 --> 00:35:45.624
that occurs and leads to a downregulation of E2

607
00:35:45.664 --> 00:35:49.384
or loss of E2 expression, which upregulates E6 and E7, causing

608
00:35:49.464 --> 00:35:52.404
critical dysfunction in p53 and Rb.

609
00:35:53.024 --> 00:35:56.383
That, along with other genetic and epigenetic

610
00:35:56.464 --> 00:35:59.944
alterations, leads to cancer. And this was the

611
00:35:59.964 --> 00:36:02.724
canonical HPV carcinogenesis mechanism.

612
00:36:04.264 --> 00:36:05.834
What our work has led to is

613
00:36:06.744 --> 00:36:07.134
this new

614
00:36:08.084 --> 00:36:12.004
schematic on this slide that shows a representation of

615
00:36:12.044 --> 00:36:15.944
the non-canonical HPV carcinogenesis that was discovered in

616
00:36:15.984 --> 00:36:19.632
head and neck squamous cell carcinoma.There are many differences

617
00:36:19.672 --> 00:36:22.892
compared to uterine cervical cancer carcinogenesis,

618
00:36:23.332 --> 00:36:27.212
including that almost all of these are caused by HPV type 16,

619
00:36:27.312 --> 00:36:29.772
with HPV 18 being very rare.

620
00:36:31.072 --> 00:36:34.482
Modest E6 and modest E7 expression,

621
00:36:35.072 --> 00:36:38.812
perhaps best demonstrated by RB1 mutations that occur

622
00:36:39.112 --> 00:36:43.022
in head and neck cancers but not in uterine cervical cancers because E7 is

623
00:36:43.052 --> 00:36:45.552
not adequate to totally inactivate RB.

624
00:36:47.952 --> 00:36:51.352
Maintenance of episomal HPV without signs of

625
00:36:51.432 --> 00:36:55.172
integration in some tumors, and E2 being expressed at high

626
00:36:55.252 --> 00:36:55.692
levels.

627
00:36:57.352 --> 00:37:01.132
And of course, more genetic and epigenetic alterations

628
00:37:01.452 --> 00:37:05.432
are required, but they're different between uterine cervical cancer and

629
00:37:05.472 --> 00:37:09.452
the two subtypes. And this is all best described

630
00:37:09.492 --> 00:37:13.472
by NF-kappa B associated transcriptional state that

631
00:37:13.592 --> 00:37:16.132
can distinguish these two subtypes.

632
00:37:18.392 --> 00:37:22.332
Most importantly, these tumors that are in the non-canonical

633
00:37:22.472 --> 00:37:26.452
HPV carcinogenesis are sensitive to radiation, and I'll get to that, and they

634
00:37:26.552 --> 00:37:29.752
have improved survival, and we've shown some of that already.

635
00:37:31.932 --> 00:37:35.852
So this slide defines the differences between the subtypes of HPV

636
00:37:35.892 --> 00:37:39.852
positive head and neck cancer. Some notable differences that we have

637
00:37:39.892 --> 00:37:43.732
discussed already are mutations in NF-kappa B

638
00:37:43.852 --> 00:37:44.582
regulators,

639
00:37:45.552 --> 00:37:48.312
HPV gene expression, and HPV integration.

640
00:37:49.512 --> 00:37:53.252
It's also interesting that some markers correlating with survival in HPV

641
00:37:53.292 --> 00:37:55.892
positive cancer differ between subtypes,

642
00:37:56.732 --> 00:37:57.232
with higher

643
00:37:59.092 --> 00:38:02.372
ER alpha PIK3CA mutations

644
00:38:03.132 --> 00:38:04.552
and estrogen receptor

645
00:38:05.392 --> 00:38:06.772
alpha expression.

646
00:38:09.852 --> 00:38:13.742
Low-risk tumors are more sensitive to radiation, and we'll

647
00:38:13.752 --> 00:38:17.472
get to that a little bit later. And most importantly, the low-risk

648
00:38:17.512 --> 00:38:20.012
tumors have better survival.

649
00:38:23.232 --> 00:38:27.072
So what I've shown so far is that HPV positive oropharyngeal

650
00:38:27.132 --> 00:38:30.432
squamous cell carcinomas can be divided into biological distinct

651
00:38:30.532 --> 00:38:33.672
subtypes with very different clinical outcomes.

652
00:38:34.952 --> 00:38:38.852
What's important here is that these differences are not just descriptive or a

653
00:38:38.912 --> 00:38:41.172
black box, or defined by

654
00:38:43.732 --> 00:38:46.232
analysis that looked for differences in survival.

655
00:38:46.672 --> 00:38:48.221
They are mechanistically grounded

656
00:38:49.072 --> 00:38:50.742
using isogenic cell lines,

657
00:38:51.622 --> 00:38:55.172
focusing on differences between low-risk and high-risk HPV

658
00:38:55.212 --> 00:38:59.092
positive subtypes, which consistently correlate with improved

659
00:38:59.132 --> 00:38:59.692
survival.

660
00:39:00.692 --> 00:39:04.112
One of the key features that we uncovered is that the low-risk subtype is

661
00:39:04.152 --> 00:39:06.332
intrinsically sensitive to radiation.

662
00:39:07.912 --> 00:39:11.592
On the right, we're looking at clonogenic survival assays using a

663
00:39:11.652 --> 00:39:15.562
high-risk UM-SCC-47 HPV positive

664
00:39:15.652 --> 00:39:19.592
cell line. In the parental cells, we see the expected

665
00:39:19.652 --> 00:39:20.172
degree

666
00:39:20.972 --> 00:39:24.552
of radiation resistance, but when we disrupt TRAF3,

667
00:39:24.932 --> 00:39:28.912
pushing the cells to the NF-kappa B active state, we see a

668
00:39:28.972 --> 00:39:32.292
marked increase in radiation sensitivity across doses.

669
00:39:33.262 --> 00:39:35.892
The difference in radiation sensitivity isn't subtle.

670
00:39:37.112 --> 00:39:40.532
The cell survival curves separate early and continue to diverge,

671
00:39:41.292 --> 00:39:43.732
and the difference is highly significant.

672
00:39:44.712 --> 00:39:45.832
What this tells us

673
00:39:46.772 --> 00:39:50.272
is that the biology defining the low risk subtype

674
00:39:50.312 --> 00:39:54.152
directly modulates survival after radiation, and in other

675
00:39:54.212 --> 00:39:57.932
words, improved survival in patients isn't just because these

676
00:39:58.052 --> 00:40:01.512
tumors are smaller or detected earlier or because of smoking

677
00:40:01.532 --> 00:40:02.072
habits.

678
00:40:03.172 --> 00:40:06.752
It's because their underlying signaling state makes them more

679
00:40:06.812 --> 00:40:09.572
vulnerable to radiation-induced cell death.

680
00:40:10.692 --> 00:40:14.172
This provides a mechanistic explanation for why the low-risk subtype

681
00:40:14.552 --> 00:40:17.972
does so well clinically and why radiation de-escalation is

682
00:40:17.992 --> 00:40:19.972
biologically plausible in this group.

683
00:40:20.952 --> 00:40:24.912
More subtly, these findings also suggest that resistant tumors can be

684
00:40:25.052 --> 00:40:26.552
sensitized to radiation.

685
00:40:29.612 --> 00:40:33.512
This slide puts the emerging biomarkers for HPV positive cancer

686
00:40:34.012 --> 00:40:37.291
into context by comparing hazard ratios for survival.

687
00:40:38.372 --> 00:40:42.332
What stands out is that the biologically defined HPV subtypes show the

688
00:40:42.392 --> 00:40:46.172
largest effect sizes, substantially greater than

689
00:40:46.312 --> 00:40:50.272
genomic or immune biomarkers. In particular, the high risk

690
00:40:50.312 --> 00:40:54.152
versus low risk HPV subtypes consistently showed a hazard ratio of

691
00:40:54.172 --> 00:40:55.712
greater than 3.5.

692
00:40:57.232 --> 00:41:01.052
I've been at a lot of talks today talking about hazard ratios of 1.5,

693
00:41:01.292 --> 00:41:04.712
1.2 at plenary sessions.

694
00:41:05.792 --> 00:41:08.142
This is a 3.5. All right.

695
00:41:09.192 --> 00:41:12.632
Across many cohorts, an exclusion of the training

696
00:41:12.732 --> 00:41:16.252
cohorts does not change the hazard ratio, as shown by the

697
00:41:16.312 --> 00:41:18.712
second bar from the top.

698
00:41:19.812 --> 00:41:23.192
By contrast, immune phenotypes and single gene

699
00:41:23.332 --> 00:41:26.392
alterations such as NSD1, ER alpha, and

700
00:41:26.412 --> 00:41:29.912
PIK3CA mutations have lower hazard

701
00:41:29.952 --> 00:41:33.152
ratios in fewer cohorts, in patients

702
00:41:34.732 --> 00:41:38.572
that they have compared. Taken together, these data suggest that biological

703
00:41:38.712 --> 00:41:42.492
HPV subtypes capture a dominant tumor behavior

704
00:41:43.412 --> 00:41:47.162
and may represent a stronger framework for risk stratification and

705
00:41:47.232 --> 00:41:50.012
therapeutic tailoring than other biomarkers.

706
00:41:55.192 --> 00:41:57.332
So success in sensitization of the high-risk

707
00:41:59.052 --> 00:42:02.992
subtype through TRAF3 or CYLD knockout led us to determine if

708
00:42:03.052 --> 00:42:06.792
NF-kappa B activation with drugs would

709
00:42:06.892 --> 00:42:08.972
also sensitize high-risk subtype.

710
00:42:09.452 --> 00:42:13.112
At the time, we were excited about SMAC mimetics because of an

711
00:42:13.192 --> 00:42:17.152
ongoing trial of zaveditinib plus chemoradiation

712
00:42:17.212 --> 00:42:20.856
therapy in head neck cancerWe tested several SMAC

713
00:42:20.866 --> 00:42:22.896
mimetics, and shown here is birinapant,

714
00:42:24.336 --> 00:42:28.266
which activated NF-kappa B, as shown by the reporter assay at the bottom,

715
00:42:30.576 --> 00:42:33.836
and in the high-risk UMSCC47 cells.

716
00:42:34.756 --> 00:42:38.516
Unfortunately, results of the TrialNEX trial, with overall

717
00:42:38.596 --> 00:42:42.496
survival shown on the right, showed that xavanapant plus chemoradiation

718
00:42:42.576 --> 00:42:45.956
therapy resulted in worse survival than chemoradiation therapy

719
00:42:46.156 --> 00:42:49.796
alone for locally advanced head and neck squamous cell carcinoma,

720
00:42:50.106 --> 00:42:53.216
and this led us to abandon this strategy.

721
00:42:53.276 --> 00:42:57.056
However, the silver lining is that this data, plus our

722
00:42:57.116 --> 00:42:59.176
TRAF and CYLD knockout data,

723
00:43:00.396 --> 00:43:03.836
showed that NF-kappa B activation was sufficient to sensitize

724
00:43:03.896 --> 00:43:07.845
high-risk subtype of head and neck cancer and

725
00:43:07.936 --> 00:43:10.656
led us to test other NF-kappa B activators.

726
00:43:12.336 --> 00:43:16.076
So I'm not going to show all of the data because of time,

727
00:43:16.176 --> 00:43:19.736
but I will show some mouse data.

728
00:43:20.066 --> 00:43:23.775
We created an immunocompetent mouse model of the high-risk

729
00:43:24.476 --> 00:43:28.276
HPV head and neck squamous cell carcinoma subtype and tested if the

730
00:43:28.296 --> 00:43:31.636
toll-like receptor 5 agonist would sensitize

731
00:43:32.576 --> 00:43:34.216
isografts to radiation.

732
00:43:35.276 --> 00:43:39.056
The spider plot and Kaplan-Meier curves show that the combination of radiation

733
00:43:39.156 --> 00:43:43.146
plus the toll-like receptor 5 agonist entolimod sensitized

734
00:43:43.176 --> 00:43:44.916
high-risk subtype tumors,

735
00:43:45.796 --> 00:43:49.196
with one mouse being cured with the combination treatment.

736
00:43:50.356 --> 00:43:54.316
An advantage of entolimod is that it was developed as a radiation

737
00:43:54.356 --> 00:43:57.386
protectant for normal tissues. So while it

738
00:43:57.556 --> 00:44:01.216
sensitizes the cancer cells to

739
00:44:01.236 --> 00:44:04.336
radiation, it makes normal tissues more resistant.

740
00:44:07.256 --> 00:44:10.756
So I hope that I've provided convincing evidence that

741
00:44:10.936 --> 00:44:14.015
HPV-positive oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma

742
00:44:14.796 --> 00:44:18.556
is not a single disease and it's not simply uterine

743
00:44:18.576 --> 00:44:22.496
cervical cancer moved north, but that it consists of two

744
00:44:22.556 --> 00:44:26.476
biologically distinct subtypes defined by different mechanisms

745
00:44:26.516 --> 00:44:30.196
of HPV carcinogenesis. These subtypes have markedly

746
00:44:30.216 --> 00:44:31.456
different outcomes,

747
00:44:32.336 --> 00:44:35.676
with the low-risk subtype showing substantially better survival and

748
00:44:35.756 --> 00:44:39.216
greater radiation sensitivity. Importantly,

749
00:44:39.456 --> 00:44:41.876
understanding these differences

750
00:44:42.696 --> 00:44:46.516
opens the door to biologically informed treatment strategies.

751
00:44:49.556 --> 00:44:53.116
And this slide really gets at the conclusions about why

752
00:44:53.176 --> 00:44:55.416
these two subtypes matter clinically.

753
00:44:56.916 --> 00:45:00.256
HPV-positive oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma has

754
00:45:00.316 --> 00:45:03.136
historically been treated as one disease.

755
00:45:04.096 --> 00:45:07.356
But doing that is exactly why large de-escalation trials

756
00:45:07.416 --> 00:45:10.896
have not shown efficacy. The low-risk

757
00:45:10.916 --> 00:45:13.776
subtype is intrinsically sensitive to radiation.

758
00:45:14.776 --> 00:45:16.996
These patients do extremely well,

759
00:45:17.936 --> 00:45:18.206
and they are

760
00:45:19.376 --> 00:45:22.225
the appropriate population for radiation de-escalation,

761
00:45:24.636 --> 00:45:28.626
to maximize cure while meaningfully reducing long-term toxicity.

762
00:45:29.476 --> 00:45:32.156
In contrast, the high-risk subtype behaves very differently.

763
00:45:33.556 --> 00:45:36.246
These tumors are not appropriate for de-escalation,

764
00:45:37.976 --> 00:45:40.656
that may compromise tumor control.

765
00:45:40.696 --> 00:45:42.156
Instead, these tumors require

766
00:45:42.956 --> 00:45:45.016
standard or intensified local therapy.

767
00:45:46.596 --> 00:45:49.956
Importantly, this isn't a group that we should treat more

768
00:45:49.976 --> 00:45:53.896
aggressively or just treat more aggressively, it's also a group where

769
00:45:53.956 --> 00:45:55.276
biology gives us leverage.

770
00:45:58.036 --> 00:46:01.876
One new therapy that I've not discussed here is demethylation that's

771
00:46:01.916 --> 00:46:05.636
based on excess genome methylation seen in HPV-positive

772
00:46:05.676 --> 00:46:08.336
tumors, particularly the high-risk subtype.

